<p><a name="top"></a></p>
<h1>ESSUM23475 - Shares that may be awarded: Additional rights conferred on other shareholders</h1>
<p>Examples of unacceptable restrictions on participants’ shares as a result of greater rights being given to other shareholders, include</p>
<ul>
<li>inferior dividend rights for shares held by employees</li>
<li>other shareholders being given priority over employees in: </li>
<ul>
<li>applying for new share issues, or </li>
<li>in applying to purchase "general pre-emption" shares. </li>
</ul>
</ul>
<p>The general pre-emption provisions may need to be examined in detail for two different reasons</p>
<p>(a) to ensure that they do not impose on the eligible shares restrictions that do not attach to other ordinary shares in the company (see <a href="ESSUM23470.htm">ESSUM23470</a> and below),</p>
<p>and</p>
<p>(b) in cases where the Articles of Association contain employee pre-emption provisions, to ensure that the general pre-emption procedures satisfy the requirements of paragraph 33(3)(c) (see <a href="ESSUM23490.htm">ESSUM23490</a>).</p>
<p>Trusts are often given priority in general pre-emption provisions, particularly Family Trusts and Employee Benefit Trusts.  Where a trust (or other named person) has such a priority right whether or not it actually holds shares, the right does not attach to any shares it may hold. It does not therefore amount to a restriction on shares held by other shareholders, such as employees.</p>
<p>Additional rights are sometimes given (for example as part of the general pre-emption provisions) to those shareholders holding a particular percentage of the issued share capital.  As scheme participants are limited in the size of their holdings by the material interest requirements of paragraph 19, this may result in other shareholders having greater rights than are available to SIP participants, whose shares will be restricted by comparison.</p>
<p>Articles of Association often permit transfers of shares to Trusts without going through the full general pre-emption transfer procedure.  These are often referred to as “permitted transfers” or "privileged transfers".</p>
<ol>
<li>If all shareholders can transfer shares on these terms this will not result in their shares being restricted. But if, for example, the Articles only provide that certain shareholders may transfer shares on these terms (e.g. to their family trusts) such a right will be a restriction on the other shares of the same class.</li>
<li>If the Articles also contain employee pre-emption provisions this may mean that the requirements of paragraph 33(3) are not satisfied (see <a href="ESSUM33490.htm">ESSUM33490</a>).</li>
</ol>
